[[File:Geographica restituta per globi trientes - Norman B. Leventhal Map Center at the BPL.jpg|thumb|250px|Geographica restituta per globi trientes (1618) by Franciscus Haraeus]] '''Franciscus Haraeus''' (Latinised form of '''Franciscus Verhaer'''; also known as '''Frans Verhaer'''),<ref>B.A. Vermaseren. De katholieke nederlandsche geschiedschrijving. p 223</ref> ([[Utrecht]] 1555? - [[Leuven]], 11 January 1631), was a "Netherlandish"<ref>He was born in the still undivided [[Habsburg Netherlands]] in a part that would become the Dutch Republic, but spent a large part of his life in the Spanish Netherlands that would later become Belgium; both The Netherlands and Belgium could therefore claim him.</ref> [[theologian]], [[historian]], and [[cartographer]]. He is best known for his history (from a Catholic point of view) of the [[Dutch Revolt]]. He was one of the first cartographers who made [[thematic map]]s and globes.
==Life== Haraeus first attended the [[Latin school]] of the [[Brethren of the Common Life]] in Utrecht and subsequently studied theology at the [[Old University of Leuven|University of Louvain]] under [[Thomas Stapleton (theologian)|Thomas Stapleton]] and [[Molanus|Johannes Molanus]].<ref name=Repertorium>{{cite web|last=Haitsma Mulier|first=E.O.G. and Anton van der Lem (eds.) (1990)|title=Repertorium van Geschiedschrijvers in Nederland 1500-1800|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/hait001repe01_01/hait001repe01_01_0309.php#a309|publisher=The Hague|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>{{rp|172}} He was ordained a Roman Catholic priest at an early age, probably in 1578. He was appointed as a professor of [[rhetoric]] at the then-new [[University of Douai]] where he also obtained a [[Licentiate of Theology]]. In 1581 he accompanied the [[papal legate]] [[Antonio Possevino|Possevin]] on an embassy to [[John III of Sweden]] and [[Ivan the Terrible]].<ref name="Van der Aa">{{cite web|last=Van der Aa|first=A.J. (1867)|title=Biographisch woordenboek der Nederlanden, deel 8-1|url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/aa__001biog09_01/aa__001biog09_01_0343.php#h0343|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>{{rp|165}}<ref name=NNBW>{{cite web|last=Molhuysen|first=P.C and P.J. Blok (eds.) (1927)|title=Nieuw Nederlandsch Biografisch Woordenboek,deel 7| url=http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/molh003nieu07_01/molh003nieu07_01_1004.php|publisher=Sijthoff, Leiden|accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref>{{rp|529}}
Back in the [[Dutch Republic]] he became a [[Canon (priest)|canon]] at [[St. John's Cathedral ('s-Hertogenbosch)]], later [[Dean (Christianity)|dean]] in [[Duinkerken]] and professor of theology at [[Tongerlo Abbey]]. In 1604-1609 he worked as a priest in Utrecht where he was in contact with [[Aernout van Buchel|Buchelius]]. After 1609 he moved permanently to the [[Spanish Netherlands]] where he became the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] of a [[nunnery]] in [[Antwerp]], before becoming a canon in [[Namur, Belgium|Namur]] in 1617, and after 1621 in Leuven.<ref name ="Repertorium" />{{rp|172}} He died in the latter city on 11 January 1631,<ref>According to both Van der Aa and Molhuyzen/Blok he died in 1632 but more modern sources like Haitsma Mulier give 1631 as year of death.</ref> and was buried in the St. Peter Church in Leuven, near the tomb of Thomas Stapleton.<ref name="Van der Aa" />{{rp|165}}
==Historical works== Haraeus wrote (or maybe better, compiled) a large number of [[Hagiography|hagiographies]]. However, his historical works of longer lasting import concerned the first part of the [[Eighty Years' War]] through which he had lived himself. He took clearly the side of king [[Philip II of Spain]] against [[William the Silent]] which gave his work a [[polemic]]al and sometimes biased character. His first publication in this field was ''Onpartijdighe Verklaringhe der oorsaken der Nederlantsche oorloghs sedert 't jaer 1566 tot 1608''<ref>Impartial explanation of the causes of the Dutch war since the year 1566 till 1608.</ref> (Antwerp 1612). This provoked a critical reply by the Dutch-Supreme-Court Justice [[François Vranck]], entitled: ''Wederlegghinghe van een seker Boecxke uytghegheven bij Franchois Verhaer, ghenaemt onpartijdighe verclaringhe der oorsaken van de Nederlantsche Oorloghe, sedert den Jare 1566 tot ten Jare 1608 toe''<ref>Refutation of a certain booklet published by Franchois Verhaer, entitled ... etc.</ref>(published posthumously, 1618). Meanwhile, Haraeus had already started on his major history: ''Annales ducum seu principum Brabantiae totiusque Belgii tomi tres: quorum primo solius Brabantiae, secundo Belgii uniti principum res gestae, tertio Belgici tumultus usque ad inductas anno MDCIX pactas, enarrantur''<ref>Annals of the dukes or princes of Brabant and the entire Netherlands in three volumes: which are firstly Brabant alone, secondly the acts of the Prince of the united Netherlands, thirdly the Dutch troubles all the way up to the adventitious 1609 treaty, which they explain in detail.</ref> (Antwerp 1623). This work was well received in the Spanish Netherlands where it long was a "best seller," not so much because of its originality, but because of its tenor. The third volume was reworked by its author, but this version only exists in manuscript; it was never printed.<ref name="NNBW" />{{rp|530}}
==Cartographic work<ref>{{cite book|last=Van der Krogt|first=Peter C.J. and Günter Schilder|title=Het kartografische Werk van de Theoloog-Historicus Franciscus Haraeus (ca. 1555-1631) Annalen van de Koninklijke Oudheidkundige Kring van het Land van Waas|year=1984}}</ref> == Haraeus was one of several clergymen from the Netherlands who around the turn of the 17th century made important contributions to the young science of map-making (another one was [[Petrus Plancius]]). He was one of the three cartographers in the Spanish Netherlands who kept the craft of globe-making alive there after the exodus of many cartographers around the turn of the 17th century.<ref name=Krogt>{{cite web|last=Van der Krogt|first=P.C.J.|title=Globi Neerlandici: De globeproduktie in de Nederlanden|url=http://cartography.geog.uu.nl/research/phd/vanderkrogt.html|work=Utrecht Cartography Dissertations 1989|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> In 1614 he published a six-[[Gore (segment)|gore]] map entitled ''Novus typus orbis ipsus globus, ex Analemmate Ptolomaei diductus''<ref>New image of the world as a globe, derived from the ''Analemmata'' of [[Ptolemy]].</ref> This was one of the first instances of a [[thematic map]] as it showed the dispersion of Christianity and Islam at the time, using [[Map symbolization|map symbols]] developed by [[Jodocus Hondius]] in his ''Designatio Orbis Christiani'' (1607)<ref>Outmapping of the Christian World.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Novus typus orbis ipsus globus, ex Analemmate Ptolomaei diductus 1614|url=http://www.shop.nsw.gov.au/agencypubdetail.jsp?agency=85&publicationId=9202&categoryid=15&subcategoryid=67|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>
In 1624 a map entitled ''Lumen Historiarum per Orientem''<ref>Light of histories over the East.</ref> was published by [[Balthasar I Moretus|Balthasar Moretus]] as part of a new edition of [[Ortelius]]' ''Theatrum orbis terrarum Parergon''<ref>Appendix to ''Theatrum orbis terrarum'' or Theater of the Lands of the World.</ref> which recognized Haraeus as its maker.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lumen Historiarum per Orientem|url=http://hdl.huntington.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/p15150coll4/id/3319/rec/20|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> This map was part of a set of two made earlier by Haraeus and designed as a catchall guide to sacred geography.<ref name=Shalev>{{cite book|last=Shalev|first=Zur|title=Sacred Words and Worlds: Geography, Religion, and Scholarship, 1550-1700|year=2011|publisher=Brill|pages=233–234}}</ref>
As a final example, Haraeus ''Geographica restituta per globi trientes ''<ref>Geography set up by thirds of a globe.</ref> (1618; see the illustration above) shows the world in three globe-gores. Note the insets: there is a map representing the 2nd-century worldview of Ptolemy in the lower-Eastern section, and a legend for the map in the lower-center, explaining symbols which identify religious habitations (a cross for Christian regions, a crescent for Islam, and a slanted arrow for barbarians).<ref>{{cite web|last=Norman B. Leventhal map center|title=Geographica restituta per globi trientes|url=http://maps.bpl.org/id/m8797|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>
