{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}
This is a sublist of [[List of names in English with counterintuitive pronunciations]].

Pronunciations for the following common suffixes are regular pronunciations, despite being counterintuitive at first glance:
* -b(o)rough and -burgh – {{IPAc-en|b|r|ə}}
* -bury – {{IPAc-en|b|r|i|}}
* -cester – {{IPAc-en|s|t|ər}}<ref>e.g. [[City of Leicester]] which follows e.g. [[Towcester]], [[Rocester]] and [[Alcester]] – {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɒ|l|s|t|ər}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɔː|l|s|t|ər}}</ref><!--Also applies for Gloucester and Worcester, which have a counter-intuitive first syllable-->
* -combe – generally {{IPAc-en|k|ə|m}}, although {{IPAc-en|k|uː|m}} in some cases (e.g. [[Templecombe]], [[Woolacombe]]) and in the standalone word 'combe' or 'coombe' (including in place names such as [[Castle Combe]] and [[Coombe Bissett]]).
* -gh – silent <!-- The intuitive exceptions are many and except for 'f' should not be listed-->
* -ham – {{IPAc-en|ə|m}} <!--Intuitive ones listed-->
* -holm(e) – {{IPAc-en|h|oʊ|m}}, {{IPAc-en|ə|m}}
* -shire – {{IPAc-en|ʃ|ɪər|,_|ʃ|ər}}
* -quay - {{IPAc-en|k|iː}}
* -wich - {{IPAc-en|ɪ|tʃ}}, {{IPAc-en|ɪ|dʒ}}<ref>Well-known, large examples are [[Woolwich]] and [[West Bromwich]] cf. [[Nantwich]] and [[Droitwich Spa]]</ref>
* -wick – {{IPAc-en|ɪ|k}}<ref>e.g. [[Smethwick]], [[Chiswick]] and [[Flitwick]]</ref>'''{{#tag:ref|Accordingly: [[Southwick, Hampshire|Southwick]], [[Hampshire]] - {{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|ʌ|ð|ᵻ|k}} <br/>Anomalies: [[Southwick, West Sussex|Southwick]], [[West Sussex]] is pronounced {{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|aʊ|θ|w|ᵻ|k}}, like [[Painswick]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[Prestwick]] and [[Hardwick (disambiguation)|Hardwick]] as well as [[Pickwick, Wiltshire|Pickwick]] a former village in Wiltshire through which the novel [[The Pickwick Papers]] got its title, but these by population represent a very small minority.|group= n}}
* -mouth – {{IPAc-en|m|ə|θ}} in some cases (e.g. [[Bournemouth]], [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]], [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]]), {{IPAc-en|m|aʊ|θ}} in others (e.g. [[Avonmouth]], [[Lossiemouth]], [[Tynemouth]]).
Pronunciation of the following common prefix is variable depending on dialect:
* Al- {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɒ|l|,_|ˈ|ɔː|l}}

